column45: Reef front environment consisting of two reef tracts. Lower reef tract is mosty patch reefs of Platygyra acuta. There is a transition in the upper reef tract from massive corals (D. strigosa, Platygyra) to branching corals (G. fasicularis, A. porites). Upper reef tract corals are clast-supported and are found alongside mollusk, echinoid, and bivalve fossils.

A major scarp commencing at around C170 m and terminating

in a prominent wide plateau at 230 m. At 204 to 210 m,

from the reef slope at C191 m elevation and the sample Favide

204 m came from the reef edge at +204 m elevation.

column45: Slumped feature. Near the Com 2 profile relatively flat surfaces branch off from one another and are all back-tilted to the southeast. Landslide scarps are also visible near the coast. These observations could be a combination of primary depositional features or faulted/slumped features. A stratigraphic study and more detailed mapping could possibly constrain the cause of tilting. Several samples (Com-19a, Com-19b, Com-21, Com-26a, Com-27, Com-45b, and Com-46) were collected to constrain the age range of these surfaces.

column43: Used the mean uplift rate derived by Dia et al., 1997 and Collier et al., 1992 (plus arbitrary ± 0.2 uncertainty) based on correlation of coral terraces to highstands and assumed past sea levels. Dia et al., 1997 state that the uplift rate could be as high as 0.5 m/kyr, but 0.3 m/kyr is also supported by previous studies (Collier et al., 1992). Minimum rate estimate. column4:
The U/Th dating was taken from  a single unaltered

skeleton of Montastraea annularis . The analyzed sample was

collected in situ approximately 1.5 m above sea-level from

the fossil fringing reef near 'South Point'. The dating was

carried out by Steve Short at Lucas Heights Research Laboratories

(Lucas Heights, NSW, Australia) and yielded an age

of 118.8 + 11.0 -10.1 ka. B.P.

column29: The coordinates of the sample are not reported, we added the estimated coordinates of the sampling site calculated with google earth based on a low resolution map of the paper.

column29: I estimated them using GoogleEarth and the location map including a description in Mazzullo, 2006.
column37: I used the elevation reported by Mazzullo (2006), which explicitly states "above MSL" on page 1021.
column43: They estimate subsidence of 39 mm/ky based on an assumed MIS5e elevation of 6 m.  But this is circular reasoning for some uses of this data.
column57: The original authors use the elevations range of Lighty et al. (1982) for Acropora palmata in the Caribbean (0-5 m).  Using the facies analysis of Mazzullo (2006) I assume this is a reef flat, thus the given indicative meaning.

column9:
Gischler et al., 2000
 Simms, 2021
column29: I estimated them using GoogleEarth and their location map in Gischler and Lomando (1999 - JSR).
column37: Very few details on the methods and datums, other than an "elevation" thus I assumed mean sea level and assigned an uncertainty of +/-1 m.  The modern tidal range in the region is < 0.5 m.
column43: They estimate subsidence of 112-119 mm/ky based on an assumed MIS5e elevation of 6 m.  But this is circular reasoning for some uses of this data.
column52: They cite other workers in the region (James and Ginsburg, 1979 and Cairns, 1982) for this species.  They also suggest this sample came from the shallower depth range based on the co-occurence of A. palmata in the cores.
column57: They use the depth ranges from James and Ginsburg, 1979 and Cairns, 1982 for Montastraea annularis in the Caribbean.  However, the paper suggest this species was found with other specimens of Acropora palmata - although not many details given.  Thus although strictly speaking this coral would suggest sea levels of 0.7+8.6/-7.3 (based on Hibbert et al., 2016) it may represent RSLs as deep as -7.5+1.2/-7.9 m using the accompanying A. palmata depth range.

column29: GPS coordinates
column37: Elevations were obtained using a TruPulse 360R laser rangefinder mounted on a tripod. Through repeated surveys, it is determined that this survey method introduced a vertical elevation uncertainty of ±0.1m. Elevations were then corrected to the water level at the time of survey and normalized to the present mean sea level using actual hourly tide gauge data for  Currimao Port from NAMRIA.
column57: Not reported
column93: Age corrections, relative to chemistry date, were calculated using an estimated atomic 230Th/232Th ratio of 4 (± 2) x 10ˆ-6 (Shen et al., 2008). Uncertainties of isotopic compositions and 230Th ages are two-sigma (2σ) level or two standard deviations of the mean (2σm), unless otherwise noted.

column44: The Hato (Upper) unit of the "Lower Terrace" Curazao
column45:
The Lower Terrace is composed of two reef units, Hato (upper) and Cortalein (lower). The contact between these two units is often seen in a topographic break in coastal exposures, where a ledge in the Cortalein unit is apparent. Thus, from a geomorphic point of view, the interglacial coral reef record on Curaçao differs from those in other areas, both uplifting coasts and tectonically

stable coasts. Curaçao represents a hybrid of these two types of coasts, with a marine terrace staircase-like geomorphology

being present, similar to Barbados and Haiti. Within the Lower Terrace, however, the reef stratigraphic record more closely resembles the stacked limestone sequences found in the Florida Keys and Cayman Islands. At exposures near the seaward side of the Lower Terrace, is observed both the Hato and Cortalein units are characterized by an Acropora palmata-dominated reef-crest facies, with corals in growth position.
column52: 0 to 5 m, associated with reef crest facies
column57: associated with reef crest facies

column62: Open-system ages calculated using method of Thompson et al. (2003), but using half-lives of Cheng et al. (2013)
column65: The U–Th spike is calibrated against a solution of uranium ore from the Schwartzwalder Mine that has yielded concordant U/Pb ages (Ludwig et al., 1985) and sample-to-sample agreement of 234U/238U and 230Th/238U (Ludwig and Paces, 2002). In addition, an in-house, carefully homogenized, aragonitic fossil coral of last interglacial age (~120 ka) is used for run-to run checks. Ages were calculated using a half-life of 75,584 years for 230Th and a half-life of 245,620 years for 234U (Cheng et al., 2013).
column93: Full details on analytical methods are reported in section 3.2 of the reference paper.

column37: The study used present mean sea level (pmsl). Elevation uncertainty is not reported. The method of elevation measurement was not described in the study but is best described in the paper of Ringor et al. (2004) and Maeda et al. (2004) (Omura is a co-author in both studies). Based on Ringor et al., (2004): "Detailed survey using an Electronic Distance Measurement (EDM) system accurate to within 3mm and hand leveling was done. Terrace elevations were corrected to present mean sea level using the predicted tidal data at Tagbilaran, Bohol." Based on Maeda et al. (2004): "an uplifted terrace or tidal notch is considered for measurement if it is laterally continuous for at least a few tens of meters. At each site, representative coastal profiles are established using a hand or automatic level. Elevations are normalized to the present mean sea level (pmsl) based on predicted tides at the nearest tide station."

column45: Conglomerate clasts ranging from 1 cm to nearly 2 m and composed of well-cemented finegrained grainstone. Grainstone clasts are angular and only locally reworked. column44: The Hato (Upper) unit of the "Lower Terrace" Curacao
column45: The Lower Terrace is composed of two reef units, Hato (upper) and Cortalein (lower). The contact between these two units is often seen in a topographic break in coastal exposures, where a ledge in the Cortalein unit is apparent. Thus, from a geomorphic point of view, the interglacial coral reef record on Curaçao differs from those in other areas, both uplifting coasts and tectonically stable coasts. Curaçao represents a hybrid of these two types of coasts, with a marine terrace staircase-like geomorphology being present, similar to Barbados and Haiti. Within the Lower Terrace, however, the reef stratigraphic record more closely resembles the stacked limestone sequences found in the Florida Keys and Cayman Islands. At exposures near the seaward side of the Lower Terrace, is observed both the Hato and Cortalein units are characterized by an Acropora palmata-dominated reef-crest facies, with corals in growth position.
